# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chuck-tanner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The **1955 major league baseball season** began on April 11, 1955.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 25, with the Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 52nd World Series on September 28 and ended with Game 7 on October 4.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In the sixth iteration of this Subway Series World Series matchup, The Dodgers defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their first championship in franchise history.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first World Series between the two teams to see the Dodgers win over the Yankees.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Giants from the 1954 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 22nd All-Star Game was held on July 12 at Milwaukee County Stadium in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, home of the Milwaukee Braves.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] In a continuation of the relocation trend that began in 1953, a team moved for the third consecutive year.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Athletics moved from Philadelphia to Kansas City, Missouri, leaving Philadelphia as a one-team city.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] On April 14, the New York Yankees became the 13th team to break baseball's color line when they called up Elston Howard.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The 1955 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and would be used until 1961 in the American League and 1962 in the National League.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 11, featuring four teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 25, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1953.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between September 28 and October 4.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (2 in AL, 1 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles had two tie games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Athletics had one tie game each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers and Chicago Cubs had one tie game each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 4 with the Brooklyn Dodgers defeating the New York Yankees in the 1955 World Series in seven games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] With the relocation of the Philadelphia Athletics from Philadelphia, Pennsylvania to Kansas City, Missouri as the Kansas City Athletics, they leave Connie Mack Stadium (where they played 46 seasons) and move into Municipal Stadium.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] They would go on to play there for 13 seasons through 1967, before again relocating.
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The *Game of the Week* moved from ABC to CBS (the rights were actually set up through the Falstaff Brewing Corporation).
[src:chuck-tanner/1955-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series aired on NBC.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The **1957 major league baseball season** began on April 15, 1957.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Milwaukee Braves and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 54th World Series on October 2 and ended with Game 7 on October 10.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Braves defeated the Yankees, four games to three, capturing their second championship in franchise history, their first since 1914, and first in Milwaukee.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1956 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The 24th All-Star Game was held on July 9 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The National League's Brooklyn Dodgers and New York Giants played their final seasons as New York City-based franchises before their moves to California for the 1958 season, leaving New York City without a National League team until the founding of the expansion New York Mets in 1962.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] On April 22, the Philadelphia Phillies became the 14th team in professional baseball to break the color line when they fielded John Kennedy.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The 1957 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 15, featuring the Baltimore Orioles and Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring all eight NL teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season since 1953 that both leagues opened on different days.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 29, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend from 1955.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 2 and October 10.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] During the Winter Meetings in Chicago on December 6–8, 1956, Cleveland general manager and minority-owner Hank Greenberg proposed implementing limited interleague play beginning in 1958.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] Under Greenberg's proposal, each team would continue to play 154-games in a season, 126 of which would be within their league, and 28 against the eight clubs in the other league.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The interleague games would all be played during a period immediately following the All-Star Game.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] 5 tie games (2 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox and Kansas City Athletics had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and Philadelphia Phillies had two tie games each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Milwaukee Braves and Pittsburgh Pirates had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 2 and ended on October 10 with the Milwaukee Braves defeating the New York Yankees in the 1957 World Series in seven games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers would continue to play several home games in Jersey City, New Jersey as they started doing so the previous year, playing eight games, on April 22, May 3, June 5, 10, July 12, August 7, 16, and September 3.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Dodgers would play their final game at Ebbets Field on September 24 against the Pittsburgh Pirates, relocating to Los Angeles, California at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum as the Los Angeles Dodgers for the start of the 1958 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The New York Giants would play their final game at the Polo Grounds on September 29 against the Pittsburgh Pirates, relocating to San Francisco, California at Seals Stadium as the San Francisco Giants for the start of the 1958 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] CBS aired the *Game of the Week* for the third consecutive year, and began to air games on Sunday as well as Saturday.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] NBC also started to air weekend games, purchasing the rights to broadcast 11 Milwaukee Braves games, 11 Pittsburgh Pirates games, two Washington Senators games, and two Chicago Cubs games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1957-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game and World Series also aired on NBC.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The **1958 major league baseball season** began on April 14, 1958.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 28, with the Milwaukee Braves and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 55th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 7 on October 9.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup (and a rematch of the previous year), the Yankees defeated the Braves, four games to three, capturing their 18th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1956.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Milwaukee Braves from the 1957 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The 25th All-Star Game was held on July 8 at Baltimore Memorial Stadium in Baltimore, Maryland, home of the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The moves to California marked the first time major-league teams played on the West Coast.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The National League exodus from New York would go on to inspire the proposed Continental League the following year, which pressured the two existing leagues to begin expansion.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] New York went without a National League team for four seasons, until the expansion New York Mets began play in 1962.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] On June 6, the Detroit Tigers became the 15th team in professional baseball to break the color line when they fielded Ozzie Virgil Sr.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The 1958 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 14, featuring the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring all eight NL teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the trend from the previous season which saw both leagues opened on different days.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on September 28, which saw fourteen teams play.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 9.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (4 in AL, 0 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Athletics and Washington Senators had two tie games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles, Boston Red Sox, Chicago White Sox, and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 9 with the New York Yankees defeating the Milwaukee Braves in the 1958 World Series in seven games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] The Los Angeles Dodgers, newly relocated from their long-time home in Brooklyn as the Brooklyn Dodgers, leave Ebbets Field after playing there for 45 seasons, moving into Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum where they would play for four seasons through 1961.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC aired weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:chuck-tanner/1958-major-league-baseball-season] NBC began airing a special regional feed of its games in the southeast.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The **1959 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1959.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on September 29, with the Los Angeles Dodgers and Chicago White Sox as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers swept the Milwaukee Braves in a regular season best-of-three tiebreaker, for the National League title, after both teams finished their 154-game schedules with identical 86–68 records.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] This was the fourth regular season tie-breaker.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 56th World Series on October 1 and ended with Game 6 on October 8.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers defeated the White Sox, four games to two, capturing their second championship in franchise history, their first since in 1955, and first in Los Angeles.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first appearance of the White Sox in the "Fall Classic" since the infamous Black Sox Scandal of the 1919 World Series and interrupted a Yankees' dynasty that dominated the American League between 1949 and 1964.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the New York Yankees from the 1958 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] For the first time in professional baseball history, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 26th All-Star Game, was held on July 7 at Forbes Field in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, home of the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 27th All-Star Game, was held on August 3 at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum in Los Angeles, California, home of the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League, the Cincinnati Redlegs reverted to their 1890–1952 name, the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] On July 21, the Boston Red Sox became the 16th and final team in professional baseball to break the color line when they fielded Pumpsie Green, 12 years after Jackie Robinson of the Brooklyn Dodgers broke the professional baseball color line in 1947.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Red Sox were notably resistant to integration due to team owner Tom Yawkey, and only did so following a lawsuit charging Yawkey and general manager Bucky Harris with discrimination and the deliberate barring of black players from the Red Sox.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The NAACP issued charges of "following an anti-Negro policy", and the Massachusetts Commission Against Discrimination announced a public hearing on racial bias against the Red Sox.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The 1959 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 9, featuring four teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on September 27, which saw all sixteen teams play, the first time since 1957.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] Due to the Los Angeles Dodgers and Milwaukee Braves finishing with the same record of 86–68, a best-of-three tie-breaker was scheduled, to be considered an extension of the regular season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 1 and October 8.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (2 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Sox had two tie games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs, Milwaukee Braves, Philadelphia Phillies, and Pittsburgh Pirates had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on September 28 and ended on October 8 with the Los Angeles Dodgers defeating the Chicago White Sox in the 1959 World Series in six games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The San Francisco Giants would play their final game at Seals Stadium on September 20 against the Los Angeles Dodgers, moving into Candlestick Park for the start of the 1960 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1959-major-league-baseball-season] The rights to air the 1959 National League tie-breaker series were awarded to ABC.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The **1960 major league baseball season** began on April 12, 1960.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 2, with the Pittsburgh Pirates and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 57th World Series on October 5 and ended with Game 7 on October 13.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Pirates, led by second baseman Bill Mazeroski, defeated the Yankees, led by outfield sluggers Mickey Mantle and Roger Maris, four games to three, capturing their third championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1925.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The series ended with Mazeroski hitting a walk-off home run in Game 7 and is among the most memorable in baseball history.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Los Angeles Dodgers from the 1959 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] For the second year, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 28th All-Star Game, was held on July 11 at Municipal Stadium in Kansas City, Missouri, home of the Kansas City Athletics.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 29th All-Star Game, was held on July 13 at Yankee Stadium in New York, New York, home of the New York Yankees.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The American League's Washington Senators played their final season in Washington, D.C. before moving to the Minneapolis–Saint Paul metropolitan area as the Minnesota Twins for the 1961 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Expansion would also see the end of the 154-game schedule in favor of a 162-game schedule.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Following the end of the previous season, the two leagues saw their first interleague trade on November 21, when the Chicago Cubs received 1B Dick Gernert from the Boston Red Sox, in exchange for RHP Dave Hillman and 1B Jim Marshall.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The 1960 schedule consisted of 154 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] This continued the format put in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919) and was the last season to use the format by the American League due to the 1961 American League expansion, which saw an extension of the schedule to 162 games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The National League would use the 154-game format for one more season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 12, featuring all eight teams, while American League Opening Day took place on April 18, featuring the Boston Red Sox and Washington Senators.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 2, which saw all sixteen teams play, continuing the trend since the previous season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 5 and October 13.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] 4 tie games (1 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Kansas City Athletics and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago Cubs and San Francisco Giants had two tie games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 5 and ended on October 13 with the Pittsburgh Pirates defeating the New York Yankees in the 1960 World Series in seven games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The San Francisco Giants open Candlestick Park after playing at Seals Stadium for two seasons.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The team would play at the Candlestick Park for 40 seasons through 1999.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] The Washington Senators would play their final game at Griffith Stadium on October 2 against the Baltimore Orioles, relocating to Bloomington, Minnesota at Metropolitan Stadium as the Minnesota Twins for the start of the 1961 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC continued to air weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] ABC also returned to MLB broadcasting with a series of afternoon Saturday games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] ABC typically did three regional games a week.
[src:chuck-tanner/1960-major-league-baseball-season] Two of ABC's games were always from the Eastern or Central Time Zone, while the late game was usually a San Francisco Giants or Los Angeles Dodgers home game.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The **1961 major league baseball season** began on April 10, 1961.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 1, with the Cincinnati Reds and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 58th World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 5 on October 9.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] In the second iteration of this World Series matchup, the Yankees defeated the Reds, four games to one, capturing their 19th championship in franchise history, since their previous in 1958.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The season is best known for Yankee teammates Roger Maris' and Mickey Mantle's pursuit of Babe Ruth's prestigious 34-year-old single-season home run record of 60.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Maris ultimately broke the record when he hit his 61st home run on the final day of the regular season, while Mantle was forced out of the lineup in late September due to a hip infection and finished with 54 home runs.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Going into the season, the defending World Series champions were the Pittsburgh Pirates from the 1960 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] For the third year, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 30th All-Star Game, was held on July 11 at Candlestick Park in San Francisco, California, home of the San Francisco Giants.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 31st All-Star Game, was held on July 31 at Fenway Park in Boston, Massachusetts, home of the Boston Red Sox.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The game ended in a 1–1 tie, due to a rainout following the end of the ninth inning.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] In response to the proposed Continental League, the American League expanded by two teams in the first MLB expansion since 1901, ushering in the expansion era.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The original Washington Senators moved to the Minneapolis–Saint Paul metropolitan area in Minnesota and became the Minnesota Twins, being the sixth team since 1953 to relocate, and the third of American League teams since then.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The American League therefore placed a new team in Washington, D.C., also called the Washington Senators.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Also, the American League placed a team in Los Angeles called the Los Angeles Angels.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The 1961 schedule was the first time that the American and National Leagues did not follow the same scheduling format.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Due to expansion of the American League, the AL schedule consisted of 162 games for all 10 teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Meanwhile, the National League, still consisting of eight teams, continued the 154-game format in place since the 1904 season (except for 1919).
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 22 games against the other seven teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] 1961 would mark the last 154-game season in professional baseball history, as the National League itself would copy the American League 162-game format following their own expansion the following season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] American League Opening Day took place on April 10, featuring the Chicago White Sox and newly enfranchised Washington Senators, while National League Opening Day took place the following day, featuring all eight teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the regular season was on October 1, and saw sixteen teams play.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 9.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] 7 tie games (4 in AL, 3 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles, Boston Red Sox, Chicago White Sox, Detroit Tigers, Kansas City Athletics, Los Angeles Angels, Minnesota Twins, and New York Yankees had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The Milwaukee Braves, Philadelphia Phillies, San Francisco Giants, St.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 4 and ended on October 9 with the New York Yankees defeating the Cincinnati Reds in the 1961 World Series in five games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The Minnesota Twins, newly relocated from their long-time home in Washington, D.C. as the Washington Senators, leave Griffith Stadium after playing there for 50 seasons, moving into Metropolitan Stadium where they would play for 21 seasons through 1981.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] Briggs Stadium, home of the Detroit Tigers, is renamed to Tiger Stadium.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] The Los Angeles Dodgers would play their final game at Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum on September 20 against the Chicago Cubs, moving into Dodger Stadium for the start of the 1962 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] CBS and NBC continued to air weekend *Game of the Week* broadcasts, while ABC televised several games in prime time.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] One of ABC's prime time games occurred as Roger Maris was poised to tie and subsequently break Babe Ruth's regular season home run record of 60.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] As with all MLB games in those days, the action was totally blacked out of major league markets.
[src:chuck-tanner/1961-major-league-baseball-season] As a matter of fact, as documented in the HBO film *61**, the Maris family was welcomed into ABC's Kansas City, Missouri affiliate KMBC-TV so they could watch the in-house feed of the game, which was blacked out of Kansas City.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The **1962 major league baseball season** began on April 9, 1962.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 3, with the San Francisco Giants and New York Yankees as the regular season champions of the National League and American League, respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The Giants defeated the Los Angeles Dodgers in a regular season best-of-three tiebreaker, for the National League title in three games, after both teams finished their 162-game schedules with identical 101–61 records.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] This was the fifth regular season tie-breaker.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began with Game 1 of the 59th World Series on October 4 and ended with Game 7 on October 16.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] In the seventh iteration of this World Series matchup, and their first since the Giants relocated to San Francisco from New York, the Yankees defeated the Giants, four games to three, capturing their 20th championship in franchise history, winning back-to-back World Series.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] For the fourth and final year, there were two separate All-Star Games played.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The first, the 32nd All-Star Game, was held on July 11 at District of Columbia Stadium in Washington, D.C., home of the Washington Senators.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The second, the 33rd All-Star Game, was held on July 31 at Wrigley Field in Chicago, Illinois, home of the Chicago Cubs.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] In response to the proposed Continental League, the National League announced expansion during the 1960 World Series, with a new team in Houston, Texas and a new team in New York City.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The 1962 season would see the Houston Colt .45s and New York Mets enfranchised, the latter being the National League's return to New York City after a four-year absence.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The 1962 schedule consisted of 162 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had 10 teams.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 18 games against the other nine teams of their respective league.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The 162-game, 18 games per team format had previously been used by the American League since the previous season due to expansion and was the first season that the National League used it due to their own expansion.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the scheduled regular season was on October 1, which saw all 20 teams play, the first time all existing teams played on the final day since 1960.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] Due to the Los Angeles Dodgers and San Francisco Giants finishing with the same record of 101–61, a best-of-three tie-breaker was scheduled, to be considered an extension of the regular season, and took place between October 1 and October 3.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series took place between October 4 and October 16.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] 3 tie games (1 in AL, 2 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The Minnesota Twins and Washington Senators had one each.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The Houston Colt .45s had two tie games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began on October 1 and ended on October 16 with the New York Yankees defeating the San Francisco Giants in the 1962 World Series in seven games.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] Comiskey Park, home of the Chicago White Sox, renamed to White Sox Park.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] CBS dropped its Sunday broadcasts once the NFL season started in mid-September, dropping the option clause for affiliates to carry baseball or football in place since 1957.
[src:chuck-tanner/1962-major-league-baseball-season] The All-Star Game, the National League tie-breaker series, and the World Series aired on NBC.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] A left-handed batter and thrower, Tanner signed his first professional baseball contract with the Boston Braves.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He played for eight seasons (1955–1962) for four teams: the Milwaukee Braves, Chicago Cubs, Cleveland Indians and Los Angeles Angels.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 396 games played, Tanner batted .261 with 21 home runs.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] While with the Braves, Tanner hit a home run off the first pitch in his first career at-bat on April 12, 1955.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He is the only Braves player to hit a home run in his first at-bat in Milwaukee.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner is best known as a manager, having managed four teams from 1970 to 1988.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] His overall managerial record was 1,352–1,381 in 17 full seasons and parts of two others.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner spent his entire Minor League managing career in the Angels' system.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 1963, Tanner began his managerial career with the single-A Quad Cities Angels in the Midwest League, and spent the next seven seasons climbing the Angels' organizational ladder, including managing the El Paso Sun Kings (1965-1966 and 1968), and Seattle Angels (1967).
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He won the Texas League title with El Paso in 1968.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 1970 he led the AAA Hawaii Islanders to 98 wins in 146 games and a berth in the Pacific Coast League (PCL) championship series.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Both Tanner and Roland Hemond joined the Chicago White Sox from the Angels on September 4, 1970, when general manager Stu Holcomb hired them as manager and director of player personnel respectively.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner, who signed a two-year contract, replaced Don Gutteridge who had been dismissed two days prior.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Due to the Islanders qualifying for the PCL championship series, he was unable to make his White Sox managerial debut until September 15, requiring Bill Adair to serve in the interim.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner did not retain Adair for his staff after the season, but he named Al Monchak and Joe Lonnett as his first- and third-base coaches respectively on October 2, 1970.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] All three went on to serve in similar capacities together with the White Sox (1971–75), Oakland Athletics (1976) and Pittsburgh Pirates (1977–84), with Monchak continuing as Tanner's first-base coach with the Atlanta Braves from 1986 to 1988.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] With the White Sox, Tanner managed such star players as Wilbur Wood, Carlos May, Bill Melton, and the temperamental Dick Allen, who like Tanner was a native of Lawrence County, Pennsylvania by way of Wampum.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] His most successful season with the Sox came in 1972, when he managed them to a close second-place finish behind the eventual World Series champion Oakland Athletics in the American League (AL) Western Division.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] The pitching staff was led by 24-game winner Wood, whom Tanner had converted from a reliever to a starter.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] According to Tommy John, "Tanner never liked to use a knuckleballer in relief, because of the way the knuckler danced and moved all over.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He solved that by making Wood a starter." Tanner was voted that year's *The Sporting News* Manager of the Year Award.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He also converted Rich "Goose" Gossage from a starting pitcher to a reliever, a role that led Gossage to the Hall of Fame.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He finished his White Sox career with a record of 401 wins and 414 losses.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner was replaced by Paul Richards on December 17, 1975.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Bill Veeck, who had repurchased the White Sox, invited Tanner to remain in the organization in a different capacity, but the offer was declined.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner still had to be paid $60,000 in each of three remaining years of his White Sox contract.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] John said that "Chuck Tanner once told me he never forgot the fact that he was a player.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] One day later on December 18, 1975, Tanner was hired to succeed Alvin Dark as manager of the Oakland Athletics.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] With speedy players such as Bert Campaneris, Bill North, Claudell Washington, and Don Baylor, Tanner made the A's into a running team, stealing an AL league-record 341 bases.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Eight players had 20 or more steals, including 51 by pinch runners Matt Alexander (who only came to the plate 30 times) and Larry Lintz (who had one at-bat all season).
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] However, the days of the juggernaut A's of Reggie Jackson and Catfish Hunter had passed with the coming of free agency and Tanner's switch to small-ball couldn't prop up a crumbling dynasty as the team finished second in the AL West, 2+1⁄2 games behind the Kansas City Royals with an 87-74 record.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] A's owner Charlie Finley had hoped to secure a manager at a cut rate for at least three years, but ended up in a dispute with Veeck and the American League over how much each team owed Tanner.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] AL president Lee MacPhail ruled that the White Sox had to pay most of the $60,000 owed to Tanner for the 1976 season but was released from any contractual obligation for 1977 and 1978.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner returned to his Western Pennsylvania roots when he was traded by the A's to the Pittsburgh Pirates for Manny Sanguillén and $100,000 on November 5, 1976.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He succeeded the recently retired Danny Murtaugh as Pirates manager.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] This was the third instance in major-league history where a manager has been part of a baseball trade.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] (Joe Gordon and Jimmie Dykes were traded for each other during the 1960 season, and Gil Hodges was traded by the Washington Senators to the New York Mets for pitcher Bill Denehy and $100,000 in November 1967.) Sanguillén was traded back to the Pirates in 1978.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He reached the pinnacle of his managerial career in 1979 as the skipper of the Pirates' 1979 World Series champion team.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] The team included future Hall of Famers, first baseman Willie Stargell and pitcher Bert Blyleven, along with curmudgeonly stars like third baseman Bill Madlock and outfielder Dave Parker.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner guided the team together, and the players selected the Sister Sledge hit "We Are Family" as their theme song.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] The Pirates were able to win the World Series after falling behind three games to one to the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Hall of Fame manager Sparky Anderson wrote of the Pirates, "They do everything with abandon, because that's the way Chuck Tanner wants it.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He's an aggressive manager, a manager who doesn't go by the book.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] That's why Pittsburgh is such an exciting team." It would be the only time Tanner led a team to the postseason.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Although it was not apparent at the time, Tanner's managerial career had crested.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] The next six seasons could not match his 1979 World Series winner, and the Pittsburgh drug trials showed that serious drug problems beset the team—arguably more so than anyone else in the majors.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] The most famous Pirate affected by his usage was Parker, whose cocaine habit punched a hole in his offensive production in the middle of his career.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Reliever Rod Scurry had it much worse; his cocaine habit ultimately forced him out of baseball in 1988 and cost him his life in 1992.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Following four mediocre seasons in which the Pirates neither lost nor won no more than 84 games, but only finished as high as second place in the division once, they fell to last place two years in a row, bottoming out at 104 losses in 1985, and Tanner was fired.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He finished his Pirates career with a record of 711 wins and 685 losses.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner was hired by the Atlanta Braves prior to the 1986 season.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] This was easily his least successful managerial stop.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner's Braves finished last and second to last in the NL West in his two full seasons.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Following a 12–27 start to the 1988 season, Tanner was fired by the Braves and replaced by Russ Nixon.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He finished his Braves career with a record of 153 wins and 208 losses.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] After spending five seasons as a special assistant to the general manager of the Cleveland Indians, Tanner was named a senior advisor to new Pittsburgh Pirates GM Neal Huntington in the autumn of 2007.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 2006, he was invited to be a coach in the 2006 All Star game by NL manager Phil Garner, who had played for both the A's and the Pirates during Tanner's tenure as manager.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Prior to the start of the game, Tanner threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 2007, the Rotary Club of Pittsburgh began the Chuck Tanner Baseball Manager of the Year Award.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] For the first three years, the award was given to a manager in Major League Baseball.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] In 2010, a second award was presented to the "Chuck Tanner Collegiate Baseball Manager of the Year"; the original award was renamed the "Chuck Tanner Major League Baseball Manager of the Year Award".
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] He was the father of former major league player and coach Bruce Tanner.
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner later opened a restaurant in his hometown of New Castle, Pennsylvania, which has since been sold but remains under the name, "Chuck Tanner's Restaurant".
[src:chuck-tanner/chuck-tanner] Tanner died at age 82 on February 11, 2011, in New Castle after a long illness.
